Communication Overload

Tracking Notifications to Reduce Stress

In the modern world, it can be hard to get a break from constant notifications on your devices. If you are like me, you may often feel overwhelmed by the number of notifications you receive every day. I tracked my phone data over 5 days to see what kinds of notifications I get, where they are from, and what times of day I get the most notifications, in the hopes to use this to reduce my stress about notifications.

Which Apps Do I Get The Most Notifications From

I get the most notifications from Instagram, at over 30 notifications in five days. The apps I get the least notifications from are Whatsapp, Outlook, Phone, Messenger, and BeReal, at only one each for the five days.

Whats The Point?

My Purpose Graph

I get notifications for a variety of reasons, but the most common notification I get is talking with friends. This happens on Instagram and Snapchat mostly. I get the least notifications talking to family, this is because I usually see them once a week, so dont need to constantly keep in contact.

Who, What When?

My Time Graph

I get notifications throughout most of the day, even at night (as some of my friends live overseas in different timezones). I get a large number of notifications just when Im getting up, at around 8.30am - 9.00am. Then there are another group of notifications that typically happen around 4.00pm.

Sorry For The Delayed Reply

My Response Graph

I usually put of replying to notifications for maybe too long. From this graph, the majority of messages I will reply to within 1 - 24 hours. Some I will not respond to, but these messages come from Google Calendar, Gmail, Outlook, which are just reminders or spam emails. The Instagram and Snapchat notifications that I dont respond to are typically people liking a message I have sent, so dont usually require a response.
